+# `runs doctor` — journal health checker with mechanical repair
+
+## Goal
+
+Add a `flowai-workflow runs doctor --workflow <dir> --run <runId>` subcommand
+that diagnoses a run's durability artifacts (`journal.jsonl`, node
+directories, `runs/.lock`) and, with `--repair`, applies ONLY safe mechanical
+fixes. The journal is a run's sole durable record; crashes/tampering/bugs can
+degrade it. Doctor reports EVERY problem grouped by severity and exits 0 when
+no ERRORs, 1 otherwise.
+
+## Overview
+
+### Context
+
+- `journal.jsonl` (append-only, one JSON object per line) is replayed by the
+  EXISTING replayer `replayRunJournal` in `src/state/run-journal.ts` to
+  reconstruct `RunState`. The writer (`RunJournalWriter.open`) already tolerates
+  a torn final line by truncating to the last valid byte — that torn tail is
+  the expected crash artifact.
+- Lock: `<workflowDir>/runs/.lock` (JSON `{pid,hostname,run_id,started_at}`),
+  parsed by `readLockInfo`, path by `defaultLockPath` (`src/state/lock.ts`).
+  Liveness = `Deno.kill(pid,"SIGCONT")` (currently private `isProcessAlive`).
+- Run/node paths: `getRunDir`, `getNodeDir` (`src/state/state.ts`). The engine
+  emits a `node_directory_declared` event for EVERY node up-front
+  (`engine.ts:790-806`) but only creates a node dir lazily on first artifact
+  write — so a declared dir absent on disk is NORMAL, not corruption.
+- CLI arg-parsing style: per-subcommand parser loop accepting `--flag value`
+  and `--flag=value` (`parseAnswerArgs`), thin `run*` wrapper that exits
+  (`src/cli.ts`).
+
+### Current State
+
+- No `runs` subcommand exists. `replayRunJournal` THROWS on a mid-file garbage
+  line, on missing `run_started`, and on mixed run-ids; it TOLERATES a torn
+  tail and DEDUPES duplicate `event_id`s. Unknown `kind` values are silently
+  ignored by the replay switch (no throw).
+- `isProcessAlive` is private; no exported helper classifies the lock relative
+  to a specific run; no exported runtime list of journal event kinds.
+
+### Constraints
+
+- Reuse the EXISTING replayer as the single source of replay truth — writing a
+  second replayer is forbidden. Doctor orchestrates + inspects the replay
+  result. Journal line-level integrity scanning (which the replayer cannot do
+  because it throws) is doctor's own inspection, not a re-implementation of
+  replay semantics.
+- Reuse `src/state/` helpers for run/node/lock paths and lock parsing; do not
+  duplicate path construction or lock-file knowledge. Promote the lock liveness
+  check into an exported `classifyRunLock` in `lock.ts` (centralizes
+  lock-file knowledge there).
+- Follow the existing `src/cli.ts` arg-parsing style. No new dependencies. No
+  new MCP surface, no batch mode, no interactive prompts.
+- `--repair` applies ONLY: torn-final-line removal (backup `.bak` + atomic
+  tmp+rename) and stale-lock removal. It REFUSES (clear error, nothing
+  modified) when the run is active (live lock) or the journal has any ERROR
+  beyond the torn final line.
+- `deno task check` stays green. Register FR-E83 in
+  `documents/requirements-engine/01-execution-model.md` + index + `index.md`.
+
+### Severity model (rationale — recorded for review)
+
+- ERROR (exit 1): journal missing; non-final unparseable line; unknown event
+  `kind`; replay failure; event after a terminal run event; node-lifecycle
+  event for an undeclared node; `attempt_completed` without a matching
+  `attempt_started`; replayed `total_cost_usd` diverging from the per-node
+  cost facts.
+- WARNING (exit 0): torn final line; non-monotonic `seq`; duplicate
+  `event_id` (replayer dedupes); orphan node dir; declared-but-missing node
+  dir; stale lock.
+  - `seq`/duplicates are WARNING because the replayer applies events in file
+    order and dedupes by `event_id` — neither corrupts replayed state.
+  - Filesystem drift is WARNING because the engine declares all node dirs
+    up-front but creates them lazily; disk ≠ journal is expected, the journal
+    is the source of truth. Orphans/missing dirs are advisory.
+- Cost cross-check: the replayer keeps `state.total_cost_usd` equal to
+  `Σ state.nodes[*].cost_usd` by construction, so doctor instead sums the
+  per-node `cost_usd` recorded at the TOP LEVEL of each terminal node
+  lifecycle event (`node_completed`/`node_failed`) — a redundant copy of the
+  node-snapshot cost — and compares it to the replayed total. A mismatch means
+  the journal's two cost copies disagree (tamper/bug) → ERROR.
+
